<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>I thought I would write up some notes and make a video explaining my opinion on the matter. This came up when I realized a bunch of other linux content creators were converging on the same opinion, and I thought I would chime in my 2 cents.</p> <p>TL;DR : Ubuntu hasn&#39;t contributed ANYTHING to desktop linux in 8+ years, while red hat and fedora has brought us modern Gnome, Wayland, Fwupd, libinput, Pipewire, and Flatpak.</p> <p>Notes: <a href="https://github.com/sudopluto/video-notes/blob/main/linux-desktop/fedora-domination.md">https://github.com/sudopluto/video-notes/blob/main/linux-desktop/fedora-domination.md</a></p> <p>Video: <a href="https://youtu.be/jIbh1_5NPeI">https://youtu.be/jIbh1_5NPeI</a></p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/fakesudopluto"> /u/fakesudopluto </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/linux/comments/vy6jdd/why_fedora_dominates_desktop_linux/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/linux/comments/vy6jdd/why_fedora_dominates_desktop_linux/">[comments]</a></span>